{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.02,0.2,0.64,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42580"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27522"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2119"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43199"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42580"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old man presents with a two-month history of increasing pain and stiffness in his joints. This stiffness is particularly noticeable in his hands and is affecting his work significantly. He has not noticed any fatigue, fever, or malaise. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He smokes five cigarettes a day and drinks no alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of the upper limbs, he has significant tenderness, warmth, and swelling of his metacarpophalangeal joints with associated erythema. He has no bony deformities or changes to his skin. His neurovascular examination is normal bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP: 4mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor: 100 IU/mL (\u0026lt;14)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECCP Antibody, IgG 300 IU/mL (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHLA-DRB1*04 genotype negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Given the most likely diagnosis, which one of the following is the most important indicator of a poor prognosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duration of symptoms for two months","Absence of systemic features","Male gender","Elevated serum autoantibodies","Normal CRP"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has rheumatoid arthritis, given his age, gender, risk factors, history of inflammatory arthropathy, and joint distribution of signs on examination. In rheumatoid arthritis, \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated serum autoantibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with a worse prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient has only had \u003Cstrong\u003Esymptoms for two months\u003C/strong\u003E and is now presenting for work-up, he is likely to begin treatment soon. Commencing treatment early in the disease course (usually before three months symptom duration) is associated with a better prognosis in rheumatoid arthritis patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of systemic features is associated with a poor prognosis, not an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of systemic features.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale gender\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a better prognosis than the female gender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA high CRP is a poor prognostic factor in rheumatoid arthritis; thus, this patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal CRP\u003C/strong\u003E is a good prognostic factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In rheumatoid arthritis, elevated serum autoantibodies are associated with a worse prognosis.","Aim to begin treatment in rheumatoid arthritis before three months of symptom duration, as this is associated with better prognosis."],"references":["Smolen JS, Aletaha D, McInnes IB. Rheumatoid arthritis. Lancet. 2016; 388:2023-38."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27522"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27522"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-12T16:44:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-12T16:44:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42580"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda